    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Simsia amplexicaulis improperly include inducing nausea and vomiting due to its toxic and irritant properties which can cause irritation to the gastrointestinal tract and lead to the onset of these symptoms. The plant's toxic compounds can also cause diarrhea as the body attempts to eliminate the toxins. Additionally, Simsia amplexicaulis has been known to induce nausea and cause gastrointestinal upset leading to further complications. The improper use of this plant can lead to severe gastrointestinal distress including diarrhea and vomiting. These side effects occur due to the plant's toxic compounds that can cause irritation and inflammation in the gastrointestinal tract.",
    "uses": "Simsia amplexicaulis is a plant species with potential medicinal properties, although more research is needed to confirm its uses. Some studies suggest that extracts from the plant may have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects, which could be beneficial for treating various health conditions. Additionally, Simsia amplexicaulis has been traditionally used in folk medicine to treat fever, cough, and other respiratory issues. However, the plant's medicinal properties are not well-documented, and further studies are necessary to validate its effectiveness. More research is needed to fully explore the medicinal uses of Simsia amplexicaulis.",
    "taxonomy": "Simsia amplexicaulis is classified as a species of flowering plant in the daisy family, Asteraceae. It belongs to the genus Simsia, which is native to tropical and subtropical regions. Simsia amplexicaulis is further classified as a member of the tribe Heliantheae, a group of flowering plants that are commonly known as daisies and sunflowers. The plant's classification reflects its evolutionary relationships with other flowering plants in the same family. Simsia amplexicaulis's classification can be represented by its full taxonomic name, Simsia amplexicaulis (DC.) Sch. Bip.",
    "benefits": "Simsia amplexicaulis has been traditionally used in folk medicine, particularly in Mexico and Central America. Its leaves and stems are believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help alleviate pain and reduce swelling. The plant's extracts have also been reported to exhibit antioxidant and antimicrobial activities, contributing to its potential health benefits. Additionally, Simsia amplexicaulis may help lower cholesterol levels and improve cardiovascular health due to its rich content of flavonoids and phenolic acids. Further research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Simsia amplexicaulis for medicinal purposes.",
    "parts": "Simsia amplexicaulis. The medicinal parts of Simsia amplexicaulis are reportedly used in traditional medicine. Leaves, stems, and roots are sometimes utilized in folk remedies. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of these parts for medicinal use. Further studies are required to fully understand the potential benefits and risks associated with using Simsia amplexicaulis.",
    "intro": "Simsia amplexicaulis, also known as \"Pride of India\" or \"Kanwal\", is a plant species in the Asteraceae family, native to the Himalayas and other parts of Asia. The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, including its potential health benefits in reducing inflammation, improving digestion, and alleviating respiratory issues. The bioactive constituents of Simsia amplexicaulis include sesquiterpenoids, flavonoids, and alkaloids, which are believed to contribute to its medicinal effects. The plant is commonly used in various herbal preparations, such as infusions, decoctions, and extracts, often in the form of teas, tinctures, and capsules, which are used to support overall well-being and address specific health concerns."
